Analysis - Metadata

Tom Offrede

2023-04-20

Summary of results

  • People found the room warmer at the end of the experiment in the close condition (already accounting for real room temperature).
  • People in the close condition felt closer to their partners and liked them more.
  • There was a positive correlation between all the variables referring to their perception of their partner (closeness, similarity, how much they liked them, how much they wanted to be friends).
    • But Im not sure about principal components

Thermal Comfort

People found the room warmer after the interaction in the Close condition (p = 0.02, already accounting for the room temperature). Before the interaction, there was no condition difference, and the only significant predictor of thermal comfort/perception was the real room temperature.

Correlation between RCIT variables

There is clearly a large correlation between most of the variables. But if we wanted to identify the principal components to summarize/get the average of the questionnaire scores, its not clear what items should be allocated to which components.

Hmisc::rcorr(as.matrix(m |> select(closeness, similarity, likeability, becomeFriends))) # to also see p values (all very low!)

## becomeFriends      0.48       0.68        0.69          1.00

# now do PCA (principal components analysis)

corM <- cor(m |> select(closeness, similarity, likeability, becomeFriends))
ggcorrplot::ggcorrplot(corM)

summary(pc <- princomp(corM))

Openness

Openness scores were positively related to feeling of closeness (p = 0.02) and how people liked their partner (p = 0.005). The p value of feeling of similarity was 0.09 and for wanting to become friends, 0.06.

The significant effects here are on the same questionnaire items as the significant ones in the manipulation check (closeness and likeability). So we also make sure that the participants werent unevenly distributed across the conditions: there was no difference in openness scores between conditions (p > 0.14).
